<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-22T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-22T02:00:00-05:00" n="373" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d373">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/618: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-22T16:00:00+09:00">April 22, 1939—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 23—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>194. Department’s 96, April 16, 1 p.m. and 103, April 20, 5 p.m.,
                                traffic of the Yangtze, et cetera. Emphatic representations were
                                made to the Foreign Office yesterday covering all of the points in
                                the telegrams under reference. Mail copy of our note and memorandum
                                of conversation going forward pouch April 27.<note n="54" xml:id="d373fn54">Neither printed.</note></p>
                            <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping, Hankow.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>